This project is part of Udacity nanodegree. I analyzed the world bank data to answer three key questions:¶

Q1: Which country in Southeast Asia region is leading from the GDP perspective?

Q2: Is the leading country from GDP perspective also leading from GDP per capita perspective?

Q3: Would the answer remains the same if we consider purchasing power parity adjusted GDP per capita?

import pandas as pd
import world_bank_data as wb
import random
import wbdata
import pandas
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import datetime
import seaborn as sns

pd.set_option('display.max_rows', 6)
              
def plot_indicators(countries,indicators_of_interest,indicators_description,data_dates):
    for i,indicator_of_interest in enumerate(indicators_of_interest):
        indicator_description = indicators_description[i]
        current_indicator = {indicator_of_interest:indicator_description}

        # Grab indicator for the relevant countires
        df = wbdata.get_dataframe(current_indicator, country=countries, convert_date=False,data_date=data_dates)

        dfu = df.unstack(level=0)
        sns.set_style('white')
        dfu.plot.line(figsize=(10,5));
        plt.legend(loc='best'); 
        plt.title(indicator_of_interest); 
        plt.xlabel('Period'); plt.ylabel(indicator_description);
        plt.savefig(indicator_description +  '.png')  
    
# Fetch the data

# Let's set the topic, source, region and indicators of interest for the analysis

topic_of_interest = "Economy & Growth" # Use int(topics.sample(1).index.values[0]) to get a random sample
source_of_interest = "World Development Indicators" # Use sources.sample(1).index.values[0] to get a random source
region_of_interest = "South Asia" #Use random.choice(uniqueRegions) to get a random region


# Get the topic id based on chosen topic of interest
topic_id = int(topics[topics["value"]==topic_of_interest].index.values[0])

# Get the source id based on chosen source 
source_id = int(sources[sources["name"]==source_of_interest].index.values[0])

# Get all the indicators data
indicators = wb.get_indicators(topic=topic_id, source=source_id)

# Get the countries from the region of interest
current_countries = countries[countries["region"]==region_of_interest]["iso2Code"].values.tolist()

#Period for which you want to analyse the data
data_dates = (datetime.datetime(2001,1,1), datetime.datetime(2018,12,31))

# Extra EDA - Dat is swarm plot also shows India is leading but for blog purpose I decided to use line chart as it is easy to visualize for broader audience and also the time aspect is missing in this
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib import pyplot
from sklearn import preprocessing

def swarm_plot(countries,indicators_dictionary,normalize=False,x="indicator", y="value", hue="country"):
        # Grab indicator for the relevant countires
        df = wbdata.get_dataframe(indicators_dictionary, country=countries, convert_date=False)
        df.dropna(inplace=True)
        df.reset_index(inplace=True)
        if normalize:
            df[indicators_description] = preprocessing.MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(df[indicators_description].values)
            
        del(df["date"])
        df_melt = pd.melt(df, "country", var_name="indicator")
        a4_dims = (11.7, 8.27)
        fig, ax = pyplot.subplots(figsize=a4_dims)
        plt.legend(loc='best'); 
        indicator_of_interest = list(indicators_dictionary.keys())[0]
        indicator_description = list(indicators_dictionary.items())[0][1]

        plt.title(indicator_of_interest); 
        plt.xlabel('Period'); plt.ylabel(indicator_description);
        plt.savefig(indicator_description +  '_swarm_plot.png')  
        sns.swarmplot(ax=ax,x=x, y=y, hue=hue, data=df_melt)
        plt.show()
        
# Plot chart for GDP (current US$)
